    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:45227bbf-4eb8-478b-a471-d18cb84d6d49",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a lively 9-year-old girl with shoulder-length brown hair and expressive dark eyes that, today, look glassy and tired. She is brought to the pediatric clinic by her mother, visibly pale, slightly lethargic, and wrapped in her favorite pink fleece blanket despite the warm weather. She is currently in third grade, loves drawing cartoon animals, playing with her younger brother, and attends weekly gymnastics classes — all of which she has had to skip over the past two days due to her illness.\n\n{patientName} has been experiencing profuse watery diarrhea (6–8 episodes in the past 24 hours), diffuse crampy abdominal pain, nausea, and two episodes of vomiting since yesterday evening. Her mother reports that {patientName} attended a birthday party three days ago where she ate buffet-style food that had been sitting out for several hours. Several other children from the same party are reportedly ill as well.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} appears mildly to moderately dehydrated: her mucous membranes are dry, skin turgor is slightly reduced, and she has sunken eyes. Her abdomen is soft but diffusely tender on palpation, with increased bowel sounds. She presents with a low-grade fever and a mildly elevated heart rate consistent with dehydration. She is still able to take small sips of fluids but quickly feels nauseous afterward.\n\n{patientName} lives with her parents and 6-year-old brother in a suburban home. Her mother is a nurse and her father works as a high school teacher. The family is health-conscious and active, frequently going on weekend hikes and bike rides. {patientName} is a good student and sociable child with many friends at school. She has no dietary restrictions and typically eats a balanced diet, though she is known to be an adventurous eater at parties and gatherings."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d1209359-49a4-4fca-9dd1-c0d232b030f3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant chronic medical conditions and has never been hospitalized. She is up to date on all routine childhood immunizations including rotavirus vaccine series completed in infancy. She has a history of one prior episode of viral gastroenteritis at age 5, which resolved without complications.\n\n{patientName} has a known mild allergy to Amoxicillin, which caused a generalized urticarial rash when she was prescribed it for otitis media at age 6. She takes no regular medications. She has no history of surgery or significant trauma. Her growth and development have been normal, tracking at the 55th percentile for height and weight.\n\n{patientName}'s family history is notable for type 2 diabetes mellitus in her maternal grandmother and ischemic heart disease in her paternal grandfather. There is no family history of inflammatory bowel disease, celiac disease, or immunodeficiency. {patientName} lives in a clean suburban household with adequate sanitation; the family drinks filtered tap water and is careful about food hygiene, though the birthday party setting may have involved improper food temperature control."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
